<concept id="concept_C7F197A3D399447E9E143599A3715099">
  <title>Or and And Target Rules</title>
  <shortdesc>"Or" and "And" rules enable you to determine how strict the
	 conditions used for targeting are. 
  </shortdesc>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <othermeta name="solution" content="Target" />
      <othermeta name="topic" content="Advanced" />
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <conbody>
    <p>In an "or" rule, the current page URL could contain any one of the
		entered conditions. The text at the top of the targeting widget puts the rule
		in sentence form so you can easily tell what the targeting conditions are. For
		example, you might want to target a test to URLs that are either the home page
		or a landing page. 
	 </p>
    <p>An "And" rule creates stricter targeting rule by using multiple
		conditions. In the "and" rule example below, visitors must use the Chrome
		browser and they must be new visitors. 
	 </p>
    <p>
      <image id="image_03587CDF51C24EE4934D7464960D3F2F" href="graphics/target_and.png"></image>
    </p>
    <p>You can create complex rules by combining "and" and "or" rules. For
		example, you can combine "and" and "or" rules above to create the following
		rule: 
	 </p>
    <p>
      <image id="image_198CE8346FE94267A667C49D26776239" href="graphics/target_sentence2.png"></image>
    </p>
    <p>For additional control of your targeting rules, create an expression
		target as explained in 
